<div class="sub-question-title">Part a)</div>
<div class="step-title">Step 1: Accuracy Mark <span class="marking-code">[A1]</span></div>
<div class="step-explanation">The mark <span class="marking-code">[A1]</span> is awarded for stating that the correlation is "positive". The question asks you to describe the type of correlation. A positive correlation means that as one variable (Science score) increases, the other variable (Mathematics score) also tends to increase. Words like "strong" or "weak" are ignored, the key is identifying the direction as positive.</div>

<div class="sub-question-title">Part b)</div>
<div class="step-title">Step 1: Accuracy Mark <span class="marking-code">[A1]</span></div>
<div class="step-explanation">This mark <span class="marking-code">[A1]</span> is for correctly identifying the point (39, 10) on the scatter diagram. This point represents a pupil who scored 39 in Science and only 10 in Mathematics. The question states the pupil was ill during the Maths test, so we expect a score much lower than the trend suggests. The instruction to ignore circles around points <=30 for both subjects refers to working for part (e), so don't worry about that here.</div>

<div class="sub-question-title">Part c)</div>
<div class="step-title">Step 1: Method Mark <span class="marking-code">[B1]</span></div>
<div class="step-explanation">The first mark <span class="marking-code">[B1]</span> is for drawing a "ruled line of best fit" with a positive gradient. This means your line should be straight (use a ruler!) and generally follow the trend of the data points. The line needs to pass through the gates set at (8,11)-(8,22) and (49,35)-(49,46). The overlay is used to check this.</div>

<div class="step-title">Step 2: Method Mark <span class="marking-code">[B1]</span></div>
<div class="step-explanation">The second mark <span class="marking-code">[B1]</span> is awarded for correctly reading a value from *your* line of best fit at a Science score of 28. This is a "follow through" mark (FT), meaning you get the mark as long as you correctly read from *your* line, even if the line itself isn't perfect. The tolerance is +/- 0.5. So, find 28 on the Science axis, go up to your line of best fit, and then read across to the Mathematics axis.</div>

<div class="sub-question-title">Part d)</div>
<div class="step-title">Step 1: Accuracy Mark <span class="marking-code">[A1]</span></div>
<div class="step-explanation">The mark <span class="marking-code">[A1]</span> here is for explaining why estimating a Mathematics score for a Science score of 60 is unreliable. The key reason is that 60 is outside the range of the data provided (extrapolation). You could also say that the trend might not continue beyond the observed data, or that the pupil might not follow the general trend.</div>

<div class="sub-question-title">Part e)</div>
<div class="step-title">Step 1: Method Mark <span class="marking-code">[M2]</span></div>
<div class="step-explanation">The method mark <span class="marking-code">[M2]</span> is for finding the percentage of pupils who scored less than 30 in *both* subjects. This involves counting how many pupils meet this criterion (7 pupils) and then expressing that as a percentage of the total number of pupils (20). So, the correct calculation is $\frac{7}{20} \times 100$.</div>

<div class="step-title">Step 2: Method Mark <span class="marking-code">[B1]</span></div>
<div class="step-explanation">This mark <span class="marking-code">[B1]</span> is awarded if you correctly identified that 7 pupils scored less than 30 in both subjects. This mark is implied if you have $\frac{7}{20}$ in your working. If *no* pupils scored less than 30 in both subjects, you would have used 0 in your calculations.</div>

<div class="step-title">Step 3: Special Case Mark <span class="marking-code">[SC1]</span></div>
<div class="step-explanation">The special case mark <span class="marking-code">[SC1]</span> is awarded if you didn't get the 7 pupils correct, but you *did* correctly convert *your* number of pupils out of 20 into a percentage. For example, if you thought 5 pupils scored less than 30 in both subjects, but you then correctly calculated $\frac{5}{20} \times 100 = 25\%$, you would get this mark.</div>

